article.description: Margo Dydek scored a season-high 17 points, leading four Connecticut players in double figures, and the Sun pulled away in the second half to beat the Lynx 72-53.
article.headline: Dydek leads four Sun players in double figures
article.linkText: Sun dominate Lynx, improve to 12-1 vs. West
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Margo Dydek scored a season-high 17 points, leading four Connecticut players in double figures, and the Sun pulled away in the second half to beat the Minnesota Lynx 72-53 on Sunday night.

Katie Douglas added 14 points, Nykesha Sales had 12 and Taj McWilliams-Franklin had 10 for the Sun (14-4), who improved to 12-1 against the Western Conference. Lindsay Whalen, the all-time leading scorer at the University of Minnesota, had six points.

"I thought we played a pretty complete game at both ends," said Sun coach Mike Thibault. "We helped each other on defense, we contested shots. We shared the basketball with 21 assists. When you share the basketball it makes it fun for everybody to play."

Katie Smith and Amanda Lassiter scored 11 points each to lead Minnesota (10-9), which saw its six-game home winning streak end. Nicole Ohlde added 10 points.

However, Smith was just 3-for-14 from the field and did not score a point in the game's final 29 minutes. The Lynx, who shot a season-low 29.3 percent, went more than 10 minutes in the second half without a basket, hitting just three free throws in that span.
Minnesota also shot poorly in a June 30 loss to the Sun, making just 35.5 percent of its attempts.

"A lot of times we got open looks," said Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio. "They made Katie work for what she got tonight."

That was Connecticut's plan going into the game.

"We had the mentality that Katie could get 40 and nobody else could get anything. She can't win games by herself." Sales said. "We also did a good job on Ohlde and [Vanessa] Hayden, who are their primary scorers. You win games when you play good defense."

The Sun led 49-34 early in the second half before Minnesota cut the deficit to 51-44 on a pair of free throws by Ohlde with 12:21 remaining. However, Connecticut responded with a runner by Dydek, a lay-up by McWilliams-Franklin and jumpers by Douglas and Jennifer Derevjanik to increase the lead back to 15 points with 9:43 remaining.

Three minutes later the lead was 23 points at 68-45.

Connecticut, which shot 50 percent from the field, was hot from the beginning.

The Sun opened the game with a 10-0 run and led 39-30 at the half. Dydek scored 13 of her points in the first half as Minnesota struggled to match up with the 7-foot-2 center.

Thibault said Dydek has had a bit of a breakthrough in the past week with her level of intensity and sustaining it for long periods of time. "She also played that way [Friday] night against Houston, even though she didn't have as many points."

Dydek did not let Minnesota get the ball inside with much ease, nor let the Lynx get many second-chance point attempts.

"She's tough," Ohlde said. "She's definitely a presence whether she's guarding you or not."

The Lynx played without forward Svetlana Abrosimova, who sat out with back spasms. She is listed as day-to-day.

"It's disappointing because she was coming of two very good games for us," McConnell Serio said. "She's someone who's a spark for us. Would she have made a difference? I don't know."
